(40, 21, 7, 42, 19, 32, 35, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Entry', 'Both passages emphasize the act of placing garments on the colt before Jesus rides it. This highlights a shared narrative of preparation for Jesus'' entry into Jerusalem.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 8, 12, 9, 13, 13, 'spread their garments in the way', 'Royal Acclamation in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the act of spreading garments as a sign of honor and recognition for a king. In Matthew, the multitude lays down garments for Jesus, while in 2 Kings, garments are laid down to proclaim Jehu as king.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 8, 3, 23, 40, 40, 'branches from the trees', 'Connection of Palm Branches', 'Both passages emphasize the use of branches, specifically palm branches, in a celebratory context. In Matthew, the multitude spreads garments and branches in honor, while Leviticus instructs the gathering of branches for rejoicing before God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 8, 43, 12, 13, 13, 'branches from the trees', 'Triumphal Entry Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of spreading branches in celebration of Jesus'' arrival. The use of garments and branches signifies honor and recognition of His kingship.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 9, 19, 118, 24, 26, 'Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord', 'Connection of Praise and Blessing', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord,'' linking the joyous acclamation of Jesus in Matthew to the psalmist''s call for salvation and blessing. This connection highlights a shared theme of recognition and celebration of divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 9, 42, 2, 14, 14, 'Hosanna in the highest', 'Praise and Glory Connection', 'Both passages emphasize a call for divine recognition and praise. ''Hosanna in the highest'' in Matthew parallels ''Glory to God in the highest'' in Luke, highlighting a theme of exaltation.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 9, 43, 12, 13, 15, 'Hosanna in the highest', 'Connection of Messianic Acclamation', 'Both passages emphasize the acclamation of Jesus as a king, with the crowds shouting ''Hosanna'' and recognizing him as coming in the name of the Lord. This connection highlights the fulfillment of the messianic expectation in Jesus'' entry into Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 9, 40, 23, 39, 39, 'Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord', 'Connection of Messianic Acclamation', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase, ''Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord,'' linking the crowd''s acclamation of Jesus as the Messiah in Matthew 21:9 with His declaration in Matthew 23:39 about their future recognition of Him. This connection highlights the significance of acknowledging Jesus'' messianic role.', 'quotation', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 9, 42, 19, 37, 38, 'Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord', 'Praise for the Coming King', 'Both passages emphasize the acclamation of Jesus as a king who comes in the name of the Lord. They share similar phrases, highlighting the joyous response of the crowds during his entry into Jerusalem.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 9, 40, 9, 27, 27, 'Son of David', 'Connection of ''Son of David''', 'Both passages emphasize the title ''Son of David'' as a recognition of Jesus'' messianic identity. The blind men in Matthew 9:27 call out to Jesus using this title, while the crowd in Matthew 21:9 also acknowledges Him as the ''Son of David'' during His triumphal entry.', 'keyword', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 9, 41, 11, 9, 10, 'Hosanna to the Son of David', 'Connection of Hosanna and David', 'Both passages emphasize the cry of ''Hosanna'' and the acknowledgment of Jesus as the one who comes in the name of the Lord. They also reference the lineage of David, linking Jesus to the messianic expectations of the people.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 10, 44, 9, 5, 5, 'Who is this?', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Identity', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning Jesus'' identity. In both passages, individuals inquire about who Jesus is, emphasizing the significance of recognizing Him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 10, 8, 1, 19, 19, 'all the city was moved', 'City Movement and Recognition', 'Both passages emphasize the reaction of a city being ''moved'' by the arrival of significant figures, highlighting a communal response to their presence. In each case, the question posed reflects curiosity and recognition of identity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 10, 9, 16, 4, 4, 'all the city was moved', 'Fear and Recognition in Cities', 'Both passages emphasize the reaction of a city to a significant figure''s arrival. In Matthew, the city of Jerusalem is ''moved'' by Jesus'' entry, while in 1 Samuel, the elders of Bethlehem ''trembled'' at Samuel''s coming, indicating a shared theme of fear and recognition.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 10, 22, 3, 6, 6, 'Who is this', 'Inquiry of Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the question of identity, with the crowds in Jerusalem asking, ''Who is this?'' and the Song of Solomon presenting a similar inquiry about a figure emerging from the wilderness. This connection highlights the intrigue and recognition surrounding significant figures.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 10, 23, 63, 1, 1, 'Who is this', 'Identity of the Coming One', 'This connection highlights the question of identity in both passages. In Matthew, the crowd asks, ''Who is this?'' while Isaiah describes a glorious figure arriving from Edom, emphasizing the significance of the one coming.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 10, 42, 5, 21, 21, 'Who is this?', 'Questioning Jesus'' Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the question of Jesus'' identity. In Matthew, the crowd asks, ''Who is this?'' while in Luke, the scribes and Pharisees question, ''Who is this which speaketh blasphemies?''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 10, 42, 7, 49, 49, 'Who is this', 'Identity of Jesus Questioned', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning Jesus'' identity. Both passages feature individuals asking, ''Who is this?'' in response to Jesus'' actions, emphasizing the mystery surrounding his authority and role.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 11, 43, 6, 14, 14, 'This is Jesus the prophet', 'Recognition of Jesus as Prophet', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as a prophet in both passages. In Matthew, the crowd identifies Him as ''Jesus the prophet,'' while in John, the men affirm Him as ''that prophet that should come.''', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 11, 42, 7, 16, 16, 'This is Jesus the prophet', 'Recognition of Jesus as Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as a prophet. In Matthew, the multitude identifies Jesus as ''the prophet of Nazareth,'' while in Luke, the people proclaim, ''a great prophet is risen up among us.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 11, 43, 7, 40, 40, 'This is Jesus the prophet', 'Recognition of Jesus as Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as a prophet. In Matthew, the multitude identifies Him as ''the prophet of Nazareth,'' while in John, the people affirm, ''this is the Prophet.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 11, 5, 18, 15, 19, 'This is Jesus the prophet', 'Connection of Prophetic Identity', 'This connection highlights the identification of Jesus as a prophet, paralleling the promise of a prophet in Deuteronomy. Both passages emphasize the role of a prophet who speaks God''s words to the people.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 11, 40, 2, 23, 23, 'Jesus the prophet of Nazareth', 'Connection of Jesus and Nazareth', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' identity as a Nazarene. The first passage identifies Him as ''Jesus the prophet of Nazareth,'' while the second highlights His dwelling in Nazareth, fulfilling prophetic words.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 11, 44, 7, 37, 37, 'This is Jesus the prophet', 'Connection Between Jesus and Moses', 'This connection highlights the identification of Jesus as a prophet, similar to Moses. Both passages emphasize the role of a prophet raised by God to guide the people.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 11, 40, 16, 13, 14, 'the prophet', 'Recognition of Jesus as Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the perception of Jesus as a prophet. In Matthew 21:11, the crowd identifies Jesus specifically as ''the prophet,'' while in Matthew 16:14, the disciples mention that others view him as ''one of the prophets.'' This connection highlights the consistent recognition of Jesus'' prophetic role.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 12, 43, 2, 14, 17, 'cast out all them that sold', 'Cleansing of the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus driving out those selling in the temple, highlighting his disapproval of commercial activities in a sacred space. The actions described in both accounts serve to illustrate a similar theme of zeal for the temple.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 12, 42, 19, 45, 47, 'cast out all them that sold and bought', 'Jesus Cleansing the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus casting out those who sold and bought in the temple. This connection highlights the theme of Jesus challenging the commercialization of sacred space.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 12, 41, 11, 15, 18, 'cast out all them that sold and bought in the temple', 'Jesus Cleansing the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus casting out those who sold and bought in the temple, highlighting a significant act of authority. The similar phrasing and actions in both accounts suggest a direct connection in their depiction of this event.', 'parallel', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 12, 3, 1, 14, 14, 'sold doves', 'Temple Sacrifice and Purity', 'This connection highlights the theme of purity in worship. In Matthew, Jesus cleanses the temple where sacrifices, including doves, were sold, emphasizing the sanctity of the space for offerings as outlined in Leviticus.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
